<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/7783034-ana-clara"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1594802168i/7783034._UX100_CR0,6,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/7783034-ana-clara">Ana Clara</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    I'm wondering the same things. It sounds extremely unlikely that a 5 year old child would write a letter to someone in prison and you (Jean in this ca<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    I'm wondering the same things. It sounds extremely unlikely that a 5 year old child would write a letter to someone in prison and you (Jean in this case) as a responsible adult wouldn't read it. I think she either died or was found not guilty, because at the end they say "it doesn't matter now". If she was in jail and they found a letter like that, it would still matter. Something could be done about it, especially because there would be evidence that Ellie did write that letter in the house (the printer would have a record, or her voice recorded). It seems weird that Rowan/Rachel would keep that secret, knowing a 5 year old isn't going to suffer terrible consequences for a death like that.<br />I hate that this ending is so ambiguous. If I had known it would end like this I wouldn't have read it tbh.<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
